Thanks to the organizers and speakers alike for putting together such an interesting session!

Finally, @GoyletteChami takes a syndromic approach to understanding S. mansoni morbidity in Uganda. Data from interviews with local people were validated by Human Phenotype Ontology and natural language processing to identify 25 phenotypic abnormalities.

Stephen Spencer talks about his work with hard-to-reach communities in Madagascar. With 95% prevalence of S. mansoni, no electricity, poor access to safe water and limited health personnel for a population of 250K, there's progress to be made on several fronts.
@IamJessClark uses Markov models to understand why S. mansoni prevalence hasn't changed much in Uganda despite decades of MDA. Are these biological or operational failures? The short answer is both.

With parasitology and molecular data + a travel survey, @PoppyLamberton investigate the mystery of reinfection in a high-burden setting in Uganda. Greater parasite diversity among adults correlated with travel outside the village, indicating children are sinks not sources.
@Pres_Hoover_II uses SCORE data from Zanzibar to explore common assumptions about parasite aggregation and the distribution and demonstrates "exactly what Bob May hypothesized" back in 1977.

@Nguyen_4science masterfully walked us through experimental data on natural history traits of the S. mansoni-Biomphalaria system, demonstrating how thermal optima can influence not only transmission but also intervention success

Ines Neves @JoWebster_Group combines egg count and worm genotype data to understand whether density-dependent processes regulate schistosome fecundity, finding evidence of density-dependent fecundity for S. haematobium
Quite the #schisto session today at #TropMed20. Very impressed with the quality of work addressing important questions across a diversity of topics and geographies. Some highlights from my notes.

Thanks all for doing and sharing such interesting work at the human-animal interface. I learned a lot and will keep an eye out for your publications on these topics!

Jessica Brogdon @proctorfndn uses data from Burkina Faso to remind us that antibiotic use in livestock can promote antibiotic resistance, finding some evidence of resistance to tetracycline in households that own chickens compared to those that don't.

Using some high-powered epi methods, @MeisnerJulianne teases apart direct zooprophylactic (vectors prefer livestock vs humans) and reservoir (more livestock, more risk) pathways and the indirect pathway where livestock grazing reduces tsetse habitat availability.

Frederica Lamar, working with @klevy_uw & @MatthewCFreeman, maps chicken supply chain in Mozambique, detects Campylobacter jejuni in 100% of carcass rinses (!) and concludes that informal markets are a key node of risk in the food system that has been largely ignored.

@JoWebster_Group presents work from West Africa looking at schistosome infections snail, human and livestock populations, showing hybrid infections are very common in northern Senegal. A reminder that schisto is not strictly a human disease.

Using data from SHINE trial, C. Mutasa found few predictors associated with Campylobacter infection among mother-infant pairs in Shurugwi, Zimbabwe. Mother's infection status most closely associated with infection in kids, but who gets infection from whom?

Lilit Kazazian also @CDCgov found that CCCF virus circulates in livestock in villages with and without human cases and that nomadic/semi-nomadic sheep were less like to be infected compared to non-nomadic sheep. Spatial distribution can be discerned from routine surveillance

In evaluating guinea worm eradication program in Chad, Beth Rubenstein @CDCgov @CarterCenter finds that excitement about novel strategies may have eclipsed key prevention strategies that we know work. Need renewed emphasis on containment.
Even with some technical hiccups, #TropMed20 One Health symposium was absolutely worth getting up early for this am. Thanks to @DrKristyMurray for chairing the session. Some highlights üßµ
